40|$|In four studies we {{examined}} <b>the</b> effect <b>of</b> overconfidence on <b>escalation</b> <b>of</b> commitment in investment tasks. Study 1 (N = 105) revealed {{a positive relationship}} between overconfidence and decisions to escalate. In contrast, Study 2 (N = 121) showed that overconfidence was negatively related to <b>escalation</b> <b>of</b> commitment. <b>The</b> reversal <b>of</b> this effect appeared to emerge as a function <b>of</b> <b>the</b> public (Study 1) versus private (Study 2) context in which the investment decisions were made. In Study 3 (N = 108) and Study 4 (N = 380) we experimentally replicated this pattern of findings and found support for <b>the</b> explanatory role <b>of</b> reputational concerns. A meta-analysis <b>of</b> <b>the</b> findings from our four studies showed that overconfidence is positively related to <b>escalation</b> <b>of</b> commitment in public contexts, and that this relationship is absent when decisions are made privately...|$|R
